<div id='wikitext'>
<h1>0.7.0 Level Editor</h1>
<p class='vspace'></p><p>It appears that the level editor that was built-in to Pingus 0.6.0 doesn't exist anymore.  Grumbel posted that he was working on an editor called FlexLay back in April of 2004.  The current status of that project can be found <a class='urllink' href='http://flexlay.berlios.de/' rel='nofollow'>here</a>.  Or, <a class='urllink' href='http://flexlay.berlios.de/wiki/' rel='nofollow'>click here for their development wiki</a>.
</p><p class='vspace'></p>
<h2>Roadmap and goals for new editor</h2>
<p class='vspace'></p><p>Grumbel said on IRC that Flexlay was still pretty rough and it might be easier and better to just create a new in-game editor from scratch.  The old one suffered from poor design, so this new one should be built with a flexible design in the fore-front.  Here are some goals for the new level editor:
</p><p class='vspace'></p>
<ul><li>Ability to load any existing level, but it should only be able to save in the user's custom level folder.
</li><li>XML-based:
<ul><li>Should load as much as possible from the existing Resource XML files
<ul><li>For example, Every groundpiece sprite name should be loaded by the groundpieces*.xml resources.  So, when the user picks the "Groundpiece" button, it will automatically fill in the drop-down comboboxes with the groundpiece section names and the names of each groundpiece sprite.  Ideally, they would be able to browse through what each sprite looks like.
</li></ul></li><li>Every "Worldmap Object" should be configured by another XML entry.
</li></ul></li><li>After the user picks the object, the Modifier section on the EditorPanel will open up.
<ul><li>They can pick the ROTATE options here.
</li><li>For objects like Entrances and Exits, they can pick the <strong>owner_id</strong> as well.
</li></ul></li><li>There should be a button that displays all of the level-specific information such as Description, # to save, # of pingus, time, etc.
</li><li>There should also be a button to Play the level.
<ul><li>First, verify that the level isn't missing any vital information (at least 1 entrance and 1 exit, etc.)
</li><li>This will ask if the user wants to save this level.
</li><li>Then, save it to a temporary level and launch the StartScreen for the level.  When the level is done, resume where the user left off in the editor.
</li></ul></li></ul><p class='vspace'></p><hr />
<p class='vspace'></p><h2>Flexlay issues</h2>
<p class='vspace'></p><h3>On <a class='wikilink' href='Windows'>Windows</a> with <a class='wikilink' href='MinGW'>MinGW</a></h3>
<p class='vspace'></p><ul><li>At least on my config, I've had to do the following so far to get it to compile
<ul><li>Manually add <code>-lws2_32</code> to the <code>libguile</code> Makefile in <strong>guile-1.6.7.</strong>
</li><li>Change <code>src/scripting/editor_guile_wrap.cxx</code> line 4743 from SWIG_STATIC (or something like that) to <strong>extern void</strong>
</li><li>Manually add <code>-lguile -lguile-ltdl -lwsock32</code> to the <code>g++</code> command in the <code>Makefile</code>.
</li></ul></li><li>After compiling, however, I can't figure out how to actually get it to really run.  It bombs out with some cryptic guile errors.
</li></ul>
</div>

